[R15] {'review_id': 'pjy8C8S_32ZUCcdmPSrERQ', 'user_id': 'xNIDQfpZ-zpGlLEMdMPNWw', 'business_id': 'VSDdUwXktnvL_O0meKv7MQ', 'stars': 3.0, 'useful': 0, 'funny': 0, 'cool': 0, 'text': 'I really needed pizza, and I really miss the walk-in by the slice pizza of Italy. But Alice has nailed it. Alice describes itself as having evolved from Roma pizzerias and I would agree. In Rome I was always amazed at the different topping varieties with lots of vegetables as opposed to the meat laden US renditions, and this is exactly how Alice has designed it's offerings. I actually wanted a full meal so ordered a personal pizza (Diablo's with added spinach) and the Fior Latte Mozzarella Caprese with added Prosciutto. Portions are very generous for the price and the pizza was glorious just like what I'd expect in Italy. I have not even had pizza like this in NYC or Boston (which I have always found weird because of the storied Italian influence in these cities). My review is only 3-stars for the following reasons - the Caprese "heirloom tomatoes" were not even close to meeting my expectations and they put too much sea salt on but not enough EVOO or oregano. Remember mozzarella is already a salty cheese so overdoing the added sea salt was just too much. Lastly, I ordered the added Prosciutto to the caprese and paid an up charge of $5.50 for it, but it wasn't added to the dish. VERY disappointing. Because I obtained this meal as take-away I didn't notice until I had arrived back at the hotel. For the charge, this is totally unsatisfactory. In hind-sight the added saltiness of the meat would have been completely overwhelming in light of my comment about the excessive sea salt. Finally, when I called in to order my food, the server didn't understand the menu and I had to educate her that, yes in fact they do have a caprese on the menu. How can someone working in a restaurant not know the menu? Really?
